    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogies. Let's focus on the contract.\n\nWhen it comes to the \"reasonable control\" standard, courts typically look at whether the party had the ability to prevent or mitigate the failure. If the utility company's negligence was the direct cause of the failure, and your company had the means to prevent or mitigate the impact, then the court might find that the failure was not a force majeure event.\n\nFor example, if the utility company failed to maintain their equipment, and your company had the resources to replace the faulty equipment or take other measures to mitigate the impact, then the court might view that as a failure of reasonable control on your part. In that case, you might not be able to claim a force majeure event.\n\nHowever, if the utility company's negligence was so severe that it rendered their equipment inoperable, and your company had no way to prevent or mitigate the impact, then the court might find that the failure was a force majeure event.\n\nIt's a bit like a goblin's lair - if the goblin is hiding in a cave that's been sealed off for years, and you had the means to seal it off, but didn't",
